When you decorate your keyword functions using the [decorator module](https://github.com/micheles/decorator) you get errors while generating the documentation.

```
from __future__ import print_function
from decorator import decorator

@decorator
def failingDecorator(fn, *args, **kwargs):
    return fn(*args, **kwargs)

def workingDecorator(fn):
    def decorator_inner(*args, **kwargs):
        return fn(*args, **kwargs)

    return decorator_inner


class KeywordLibrary(object):

    @failingDecorator
    def MyDecoratedFunction(self, firstParameter, secondParameter):
        print("%s called"%(__name__) )

    @workingDecorator
    def MyFunction(self, firstParameter, secondParameter):
        print("%s called"%(__name__) )
```


When you run the documentation generation on the command line:
```
C:\temp\DecoratorTest>python -m robot.libdoc KeywordLibrary KeywordLibrary.html
Building library 'KeywordLibrary' failed: AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'decode'

Try --help for usage information.
```

The reason for using [decorator module](https://github.com/micheles/decorator) is that it correctly keeps your function signature for the documentation.

An different example using [decorator module](https://github.com/micheles/decorator) VS standard python decorator:

Keyword | Arguments | Documentation
-- | -- | --
My Decorated Function | firstParameter, secondParameter |  Here the function signature is kept |
My Function | *args, **kwargs |  Here we see the signature of the decorator |

